<div class="row">
 <div align="center" class="col-xs-12"><h4><b>Thithi</b></h4></div><!--/.col-xs-12 -->
</div><!--/.row -->

<!-- Solar Calendar ::: Start  -->
<div class="row" style="line-height:24px;">
<div class="col-xs-6">
 <div><h5><b>Solar Calendar</b></h5></div>
 <div>
  Sun moves by 360<sup>0</sup> in a year (Solar Year) and 30<sup>0</sup> in a month (Solar Month).
  Each Solar month consists of 30 days (Sun moves exactly 1<sup>0</sup>) in a day.
 </div>
 <div class="list-group">
 <div class="list-group-item">
  This calendar will be used in dasas and in Tajaka analysis.
 </div><!--/.list-group-item -->
 </div><!--/.list-group -->
</div><!--/.col-xs-6 -->
</div><!--/.row -->
<!-- Solar Calendar ::: End  -->
<!-- Lunar Calendar ::: Start  -->
<div class="row">
<div class="col-xs-12">
 <div align="center"><h5><b>Lunar Calendar</b></h5></div>
</div><!--/.col-xs-12 -->
</div><!--/.row -->
<div class="row">
<div class="col-xs-12">
 <div><h5><b>Lunar Day</b></h5></div>
</div><!--/.col-xs-12 -->
</div><!--/.row -->
<div class="row">
<div class="col-xs-6">
 <div>
  A lunar month consists of 30 tithis. One day stands for one tithi. 
  Tithi is a period in which the difference between the longitudes of Moon and Sun changes by exactly 12<sup>0</sup>.
  Each month is divided into two 
  <code data-toggle="tooltip" title="Two weeks">fortnights</code> (pakshas).<br/>
  During Sukla/Suddha paksha,
  <ul>
   <li>Moon is waxing.</li>
   <li>Moon is ahead of Sun by an amount that is between 0<sup>0</sup> and 180<sup>0</sup></li>
  </ul>
  During Krishna/Bahula paksha,
  <ul>
   <li>Moon is waning.</li>
   <li>Moon is ahead of Sun by an amount that is between 180<sup>0</sup> and 360<sup>0</sup></li>
  </ul>
  At the end of a month, Sun-Moon longitude differential will be 360<sup>0</sup>.
  It means that Moon will finish one cycle around the zodiac and catch up with Sun
  again. So Sun and Moon will be at the same longitude again. Then a new month starts.
 </div>
</div><!--/.col-xs-6 -->
<div class="col-xs-6">
<!-- -->
 <div class="list-group">
 <div class="list-group-item">
  <div><b>Procedure to Find Thithi of a day using Sun's Longitude and Moon's Longitude:</b></div>
  <div>
    <ol>
	  <li><b>Find the Difference: </b>(Moon’s longitude – Sun’s longitude)</li>
	  <li>If above result is Negative, add 360<sup>0</sup>, then the result will be between 0<sup>0</sup> and 360<sup>0</sup>.</li>
	  <li>Divide the result by 12<sup>0</sup>.Ignore the remainder and take the quotient.</li>
	  <li>Add 1 to the quotient. You get a number from 1 to 30. That will give the index of the tithi running.</li>
	</ol>
  </div>
 </div><!--/.list-group-item -->
 </div><!--/.list-group -->
<!-- -->
</div><!--/.col-xs-6 -->
</div><!--/.row -->
<div class="row mtop15p">
<div class="col-xs-12">
 <div><h5><b>Lunar Months</b></h5></div>
</div><!--/.col-xs-12 -->
</div><!--/.row -->
<div class="row">
<div class="col-xs-6">
 When Sun and Moon are at the same longitude, New Lunar Month begins.<br/>
 The name of a lunar month is decided by the rasi in which Sun-Moon 
 <code data-toggle="tooltip" title="Two planets are said to be in conjunction, if they are exactly at the same longitude">conjunction</code> takes place.
</div><!--/.col-xs-6 -->
<div class="col-xs-6">
<!-- -->
<div class="list-group">
<div class="list-group-item">
 <div align="center"><h5><b>Adhika Maasa</b></h5></div>
 <div><b>Solar year -</b> 365.2425 days (12 months)</div>
 <div><b>Lunar year -</b> 355 days (12 months)</div>
 <div>
  Once in every three years, an extra month comes (covering 10 days in each year into a month in 3rd year).
  That month is called as <code data-toggle="tooltip" title="Sanskrit word: Extra Month">Adhika Maasa</code>
 </div>
 <div>
  <h5 align="center"><b>When this Adhika Maasa occurs in the 3rd year?</b></h5>
  When Sun-Moon conjunction occurs twice in a rasi. Then, the month associated with that raasi occurs 
  for two times. One is called as Nija XXXXX Maasa and other is called as Adhika XXXXX Maasa.
  <div>
   <b>Example:</b><br/>
   Lets consider Sun-Moon conjunction occurs twice in Taurus Raasi. Then, One is called as <i>Nija Jyeshtha Maasa</i> and 
   other is called as <i>Adhika Jyeshtha Maasa</i>.
  </div>
 </div>
</div><!--/.list-group-item -->
</div><!--/.list-group -->
<!-- -->
</div><!--/.col-xs-6 -->
</div><!--/.row -->
<!-- Lunar Calendar ::: End  -->
<!-- Yoga ::: Start -->
<div class="row">
<div align="center" class="col-xs-12">
 <h5><b>Yogas</b></h5>
</div><!--/.col-xs-12 -->
</div><!--/.row -->
<div class="row">
<div class="col-xs-6">
<!-- -->
Yoga helps one to keep deep <code data-toggle="tooltip" title="pain/harm">afflictions</code> away.
There are 27 Yogas in 360 degrees.
<!-- -->
</div><!--/.col-xs-6 -->
<div class="col-xs-6">
<!-- -->
<div class="list-group">
<div class="list-group-item">
 <div>
   <h5 align="center"><b>Find the Yoga of the Day</b></h5>
   <ol>
    <li><b>Find the Sum:</b> Add the longitudes of Sun and Moon.</li>
	<li>Divide the result by the length of one Nakshatra (13<sup>0</sup> 20' or 800')
	    <div class="list-group">
		  <div class="list-group-item">
			<div><b>Converting degrees into Minutes:</b></div>
			<div><b>13<sup>0</sup> 20'</b> = (13 * 60)' + 20' = 780' + 20' = <b>800'</b></div>
	      </div><!--/.list-group-item -->
		</div><!--/.list-group -->
	</li>
	<li>Ignore fractions and take the integer part</li>
	<li>Add 1 to it and the result is the index of the yoga running.</li>
   <ol>
 </div>
</div><!--/.list-group-item -->
</div><!--/.list-group -->
<!-- -->
</div><!--/.col-xs-6 -->
</div><!--/.row -->
<!-- Yoga ::: End -->
